  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      With a prevalence of up to 25%, seroma formation is among the most common complications of
      body contouring procedures such as abdominoplasty. Small amounts of fluid are reabsorbed by
      the body spontaneously, however, larger seroma volumes need to be evacuated via puncture
      aspiration to prevent wound healing disturbances and infection, leading to major patient
      discomfort and a prolonged hospital stay. There is increasing controversy regarding the
      efficacy of surgical drains in seroma prevention. This study compares the incidence rate of
      seroma in three study arms with different usage of drains.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
